      "id": 351897,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Alcohols undergo an <i>oxidation</i> reaction to yield carbonyl compounds when treatment with CrO<sub>3</sub>. For example, 2-<i>tert</i>-butylcyclohexanol gives 2-<i>tert</i>-butylcyclohexanone. If axial −OH groups are generally more reactive than their equatorial isomers, which do you think reacts faster, the cis isomer of 2-<i>tert</i>-butylcyclohexanol or the trans isomer? Explain.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBbWNSIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--accbb8173cb57d83f0c005c506bef3c756ff2638/OChem_04_EC_020.jpg\" alt=\"In a reaction, 2-tertiary-butylcyclohexanol reacts with C r O 3 to form 2-tert-butylcyclohexanone.\">\n",
